TalkingData AdTracking Fraud Detection Challenge¶

https://www.kaggle.com/c/talkingdata-adtracking-fraud-detection

From basic_EDA.ipynb notebook, we have learned that:

  1. Data is huge. We need to think about how to manage memory issues
  2. All features except click_time are categorical and they are encoded by some unknown rules
  3. Click rates vary as a function of time (there are a lot less clicks in some hours)
  4. Classification problem is a super imbalanced problem
  5. It is also a future prediction problem. We train data in the past and predict click frauds in future. Cross validation strategy will be a little bit different in such a problem

<br/n>Notable discussion on Competition Forum: <br/n>Including feature ip in your model will hurt your out-of-sample score. <br/n>And I quote from a kaggler, <br/n>"The pattern of IP assignment in Train does not mimic the one in test. If you go by using IP value as a signal in train, your final test results will be off substantially."

<br/n>Something fishy going on in feature ip: <br/n>Overall the number of IPs (test OR train): 333168 <br/n>Number of IPs that are in both (test AND train): 38164 <br/n>Number of IPs that are in Train and NOT in Test: 239232 <br/n>Number of IPs that are in Test and NOT in Train: 55772

<br/n>This notebook will address concepts drift in feature space

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# klearn import
from klearn.eda import SeabornPlot

train_columns = ['ip', 'app', 'device', 'os', 'channel', 'click_time', 'is_attributed']
test_columns = ['ip', 'app', 'device', 'os', 'channel', 'click_time', 'click_id']
dtype = {
    'ip': 'uint32',
    'app': 'uint16',
    'device': 'uint16',
    'os': 'uint16',
    'channel': 'uint16',
    'is_attributed': 'uint16',
    'click_id': 'uint32'
}
# read data
df_train = pd.read_csv(
    filepath_or_buffer="../data/train.csv",
    usecols=train_columns,
    dtype=dtype,
    low_memory=True,
    parse_dates=['click_time'],
    infer_datetime_format=True,
#     skiprows=range(1, 59709852),
#     nrows=50000,
)
# add hour features
df_train['hour'] = df_train['click_time'].dt.hour

Look at the number of clicks of encoded IP at different hours¶

We will color code the target value:

  1. orange dot (0) is None Fraud
  2. blue dot (1) is Fraud

Objective:

  1. try to see if there is any signals useful in feature ip
  2. try to understand how ip is encoded
In [2]:
colours = plt.cm.tab10(np.linspace(0, 1, 9))
seaborn_plot = SeabornPlot(size=(14, 8))
seaborn_plot.stripplot(
    x='hour', 
    y='ip', 
    hue='is_attributed',
    data=df_train,
    **{
        'jitter': 0.4,
        'marker': '.',
        'size': 4,
#         'palette': colours
    }
)
Out[2]:
[<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f7bdc2db940>]

Wow, we can see that there seems to be some signals in feature ip. <br/n>Four strong patterns:

  1. ip with lower values has much more clicks than ip with high values
  2. ip with higher values are more likely to be fraudulent than ip with lower values (more blue dots on top)
  3. (my speculation) ip is encoded based on number of clicks (or some sort of freqency-based calculation)
  4. Again, more clicks in some hours than in 18, 19, 20, 21, 22

Look at the number of clicks of other features¶

We will color code the target value:

  1. orange dot (0) is None Fraud
  2. blue dot (1) is Fraud

Objective:

  1. try to see if those features are encoded in the same way ip is encoded

Interesting! Other features: app, os, device, and channel seem to show some signals. However, they are NOT encoded in the same way that feature ip is encoded. At least, these other features are NOT encoded based on freqency of occurence.

Key for feature engineering:

  1. Do NOT include origin feature ip
  2. Decode ip, do counts or groupby (other) counts
  3. Include hours in feature engineering
  4. Try to use ip, app, os, device to identify each unique user
  5. next_click
